    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-01-13T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-01-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="909"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d909">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Tientsin/550: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-01-13T12:00:00+07:00"
                            >January 13, 1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received January 13—3:50
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. My 23, January 12, 1 p.m. At a reception given yesterday at the Soviet
                    Embassy both the Chinese Minister for Foreign Affairs<note n="94"
                        xml:id="d909fn94">Wang Chung-hui.</note> and the British Ambassador told me
                    privately that they wished to discuss with me the matter of the silver in the
                    British Concession at Tientsin.<note n="95" xml:id="d909fn95">The Chinese
                        Ambassador in the United States (Hu Shih) on January 15 discussed the same
                        matter with the Acting Chief of the Division of Far Eastern Affairs
                        (Ballantine).</note> I felt it was impossible for me to refuse to hear their
                    views but unless otherwise instructed my own attitude will be based on the
                    supposition that the American Government is and desires to remain without
                    involvement in this matter, but the Department desires to be informed of views
                    expressed by the interested parties.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping. Peiping please mail to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
